{"title_page": "Cry of the Justice Bird", "text_new": "{{unref|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox book \n| name          = Cry of the Justice Bird\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = image:CryOfTheJusticeBird.jpg\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Jon Haylett]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = Chris Gooch - Bene Imprimatur Ltd\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Novel]]\n| publisher     = [[PaperBooks]]\n| release_date  = 2007\n| media_type    = \n| pages         = 344\n| isbn          = 978-0-9551094-8-5\n| oclc= 155690819\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''Cry of the Justice Bird''''' is a 2007 novel written by [[Jon Haylett]]. It is an action/adventure thriller based in the fictional African state of Boromundi.\n\n== Plot summary==\nIn an Africa ravaged by civil war, two women are pulled from a minibus, and are raped and mutilated. Armstrong MacKay, one of the dead women's lover, enters the country to bring her body home. During the festivities of her African wake, Mackay finds out the truth behind her violent death from the other woman's husband.\nFaced with Africa's weaken government and the ineffective Boromundi legal system, the two men decide to take justice in their own hands and seek out the murders for themselves.\nKisasi, the Justice Bird, cries out as the men set out to execute the killers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2007 British novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Africa]]\n[[Category:Novels about rape]]\n[[Category:Novels set in fictional countries]]\n\n\n{{2000s-crime-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unref|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox book \n| name          = Cry of the Justice Bird\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = image:CryOfTheJusticeBird.jpg\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Jon Haylett]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = Chris Gooch - Bene Imprimatur Ltd\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Novel]]\n| publisher     = [[PaperBooks]]\n| release_date  = 2007\n| media_type    = \n| pages         = 344\n| isbn          = 978-0-9551094-8-5\n| oclc= 155690819\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''Cry of the Justice Bird''''' is a 2007 novel written by [[Jon Haylett]]. It is an action/adventure thriller based in the fictional African state of Boromundi.\n\n== Plot summary==\nIn an Africa ravaged by civil war, two women are pulled from a minibus, and are raped and mutilated. Armstrong MacKay, one of the dead women\u2019s lover, enters the country to bring her body home. During the festivities of her African wake, Mackay finds out the truth behind her violent death from the other woman\u2019s husband.\nFaced with Africa\u2019s weaken government and the ineffective Boromundi legal system, the two men decide to take justice in their own hands and seek out the murders for themselves.\nKisasi, the Justice Bird, cries out as the men set out to execute the killers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2007 British novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Africa]]\n[[Category:Novels about rape]]\n[[Category:Novels set in fictional countries]]\n\n\n{{2000s-crime-novel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot summary:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cry_of_the_Justice_Bird"}
{"title_page": "Brett Crozier", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|United States Navy officer}}\n{{Under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox military person\n|name=Brett E. Crozier\n|image=Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg\n|birth_name=Brett Elliott Crozier<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/102nd-congress/852 |title=PN852 \u2014 Navy |date=March 3, 1992 |website=[[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1970|02|24}}\n|birth_place=[[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], [[California]], U.S.\n|allegiance={{flag|United States}}\n|branch=[[United States Navy]]\n|rank=[[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]]\n|serviceyears=1992\u2013present\n|commands=[[VFA-94]]<br>{{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19}}<br>{{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71}}\n|battles=[[Iraq War]]\n|awards=[[Legion of Merit]] (2)\n|signature=Brett Crozier signature.png\n}}\n'''Brett Elliott Crozier''' (born February 24, 1970) is an American naval captain in the [[United States Navy]]. He served as commanding officer of the [[aircraft carrier]] [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']] until being relieved on April 2, 2020 in the midst of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Courtney|last=Kube|first2=Mosheh|last2=Gains|title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier|work=[[NBC News]]|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/navy-relieves-uss-theodore-roosevelt-captain-loss-of-confidence-2020-4|title=US Navy fires the captain of the aircraft carrier stricken by a coronavirus outbreak|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|website=Business Insider|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/captain-of-uss-roosevelt-relieved-of-command-after-letter-about-coronavirus-outbreak-was-leaked-1.624691|title=Captain of USS Roosevelt relieved of command after letter about coronavirus outbreak was leaked|website=Stars and Stripes|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHe grew up in [[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], California, graduating from [[Santa Rosa High School (Santa Rosa, California)|Santa Rosa High School]] in 1988 prior to entering the [[U.S. Naval Academy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/10310811-181/chris-smith-santa-rosa-high |archive-url=https://archive.is/uI1PU |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |title=Santa Rosa High grad and \u2018Top Gun\u2019 fan now commands the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt |date=November 14, 2019 |last1=Smith |first1=Chris |publisher=[[The Press Democrat]]}}</ref> After graduating in 1992, he became a Naval Aviator and was assigned as a SH-60B Seahawk pilot at Barbers Point, Hawaii.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/lcc19/Pages/Bio1-9June2017-16June2018.aspx|title=Captain Brett E. Crozier|website=www.public.navy.mil|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> He received his Master\u2019s Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies from the [[Naval War College]] in 2007, and completed [[Nuclear Power School]] in 2014.<ref name=\"NavyBio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/airfor/cvn71/Pages/COMMANDINGOFFICER.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.is/ZJbJV |access-date=April 2, 2020 |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |title=Captain Brett E. Crozier |publisher=US Navy}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn April 2014, Crozier completed the Naval Nuclear Power training program and was [[executive officer]] of the aircraft carrier {{USS|Ronald Reagan}}. In June 2017, Crozier took command of {{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19|6}} in Yokosuka, Japan.\n\nCrozier was the captain of the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} until he was relieved by acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|US Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]], after a letter of his complaint over infections among his crew related to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was leaked. At the time of his removal, some 114 crew members (of a total compliment of around 4,000) had been reported to be positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52145230|title=US Navy removes captain who raised virus alarm|date=April 3, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/politics/uss-roosevelt-commander-relieved/index.html|title=Commander of aircraft carrier hit by coronavirus removed for 'poor judgment' after sounding alarm|author1=Ryan Browne |author2=Zachary Cohen |author3=Jamie Crawford|website=CNN|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Borger|first=Julian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/02/us-navy-uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus|title=US navy fires commander who raised alarm about coronavirus on ship|date=April 2, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Honors, awards, and decorations ==\n{| style=\"margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" |[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|220px|center]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=5|type=award-oak|ribbon=Defense Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Service Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Achievement ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Battle Effectiveness Award ribbon, 2nd award.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Sea Service Deployment Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar.svg|width=106}} \n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=United States Navy Rifle Marksmanship Ribbon with expert device.svg|width=106px}} \n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=United States Navy Pistol Marksmanship Ribbon with expert device.svg|width=106px}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |[[File:Navy_CaS.png|50px]] \n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |[[Naval Aviator Badge]]\n|-\n|[[Legion of Merit]] w/ 1 gold [[service star]]\n|[[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]] w/ 1 silver [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]\n|-\n|[[Air Medal]]\n|[[Joint Service Commendation Medal]]\n|[[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]] w/ 2 gold [[service stars]]\n|-\n|[[Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]] w/ 1 gold [[service star]]\n|[[Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation]]\n|[[Navy E Ribbon]] w/ 2 [[Battle E]] devices\n|-\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]] w/ 1 [[service star]]\n|[[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]]\n|[[Iraq Campaign Medal]] w/ 1 [[service star]]\n|-\n|[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n|[[Navy Sea Service Deployment Ribbon]] w/ 3 [[service stars]]\n|[[Overseas Service Ribbon|Navy & Marine Corps Overseas Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|[[NATO Medal]]\n|[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Rifle Marksmanship Medal]] w/ \"E\" device\n|[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Pistol Marksmanship Medal]] w/ \"E\" device\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |[[Command at Sea insignia]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Brett E. Crozier}}\n* [https://www.public.navy.mil/airfor/cvn71/pages/commandingofficer.aspx Navy biography]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crozier, Brett}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Naval War College alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy captains]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Rosa, California]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American naval officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|United States Navy officer}}\n{{Under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox military person\n|name=Brett E. Crozier\n|image=Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg\n|birth_name=Brett Elliott Crozier<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/102nd-congress/852 |title=PN852 \u2014 Navy |date=March 3, 1992 |website=[[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1970|02|24}}\n|birth_place=[[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], [[California]], U.S.\n|allegiance={{flag|United States}}\n|branch=[[United States Navy]]\n|rank=[[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]]\n|serviceyears=1992\u2013present\n|commands=[[VFA-94]]<br>{{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19}}<br>{{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71}}\n|battles=[[Iraq War]]\n|awards=[[Legion of Merit]] (2)\n|signature=Brett Crozier signature.png\n}}\n'''Brett Elliott Crozier''' (born February 24, 1970) is an American naval captain in the [[United States Navy]]. He served as commanding officer of the [[aircraft carrier]] [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']] until being relieved on 2 April 2020 in the midst of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Courtney|last=Kube|first2=Mosheh|last2=Gains|title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier|work=[[NBC News]]|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/navy-relieves-uss-theodore-roosevelt-captain-loss-of-confidence-2020-4|title=US Navy fires the captain of the aircraft carrier stricken by a coronavirus outbreak|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|website=Business Insider|date=3 April 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/captain-of-uss-roosevelt-relieved-of-command-after-letter-about-coronavirus-outbreak-was-leaked-1.624691|title=Captain of USS Roosevelt relieved of command after letter about coronavirus outbreak was leaked|website=Stars and Stripes|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHe grew up in [[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], California, graduating from [[Santa Rosa High School (Santa Rosa, California)|Santa Rosa High School]] in 1988 prior to entering the [[U.S. Naval Academy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressdemocrat.com/news/10310811-181/chris-smith-santa-rosa-high |archive-url=https://archive.is/uI1PU |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |title=Santa Rosa High grad and \u2018Top Gun\u2019 fan now commands the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt |date=2019-11-14 |last1=Smith |first1=Chris |publisher=[[The Press Democrat]]}}</ref> After graduating in 1992, he became a Naval Aviator and was assigned as a SH-60B Seahawk pilot at Barbers Point, Hawaii.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/lcc19/Pages/Bio1-9June2017-16June2018.aspx|title=Captain Brett E. Crozier|website=www.public.navy.mil|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> He received his Master\u2019s Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies from the [[Naval War College]] in 2007, and completed [[Nuclear Power School]] in 2014.<ref name=\"NavyBio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.public.navy.mil/airfor/cvn71/Pages/COMMANDINGOFFICER.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.is/ZJbJV |access-date=2020-04-02 |archive-date=2020-04-02 |title=Captain Brett E. Crozier |publisher=US Navy}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn April 2014, Crozier completed the Naval Nuclear Power training program and was [[executive officer]] of the aircraft carrier {{USS|Ronald Reagan}}. In June 2017, Crozier took command of {{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19|6}} in Yokosuka, Japan.\n\nCrozier was the captain of the aircraft carrier {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} until he was relieved by acting [[United States Secretary of the Navy|US Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]], after a letter of his complaint over infections among his crew related to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was leaked. At the time of his removal, some 114 crew members (of a total compliment of around 4,000) had been reported to be positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52145230|title=US Navy removes captain who raised virus alarm|date=2020-04-03|work=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/politics/uss-roosevelt-commander-relieved/index.html|title=Commander of aircraft carrier hit by coronavirus removed for 'poor judgment' after sounding alarm|author1=Ryan Browne |author2=Zachary Cohen |author3=Jamie Crawford|website=CNN|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Borger|first=Julian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/02/us-navy-uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus|title=US navy fires commander who raised alarm about coronavirus on ship|date=April 2, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Honors, awards, and decorations ==\n{| style=\"margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" |[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|220px|center]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=5|type=award-oak|ribbon=Defense Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}